{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a nutshell, Russell\u8217's paradox proves, by contradiction, that certain mathematical collections cannot be sets. It posits the existence of a "set of all sets that don\u8217't contain themselves". Such a set can neither contain itself (since in that case, it would be a "set that does contain itself", and should be excluded); nor can it exclude it itself (since in that case, it would be a "set that doesn\u8217't contain itself", and should be included).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that any equivalence relation over a set {\i S} defines a partition of \u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 a) \u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}} has no empty elements: any element in {\i S} is part of at least one equivalence class, the class containing at least that element itself. Since there is no equivalence class constructed independently from elements, there are no empty equivalence classes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 b) Elements of \u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}} are disjoint: suppose there is an element {\i x} that is part of {\i A} and {\i B}, two distinct equivalence classes. \u8704?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i a} and \u8704?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}. By transivity through {\i x}, \u8704?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?\u8704?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?{\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}. Therefore, {\i A} and {\i B} are the same equivalence class: {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i B}. Contradiction. Therefore all elements of \u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}} are disjoint subsets of {\i S}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 c) The union of all elements of \u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}} makes up {\i S}: suppose \u8707?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S} such that {\i x}\u8196?\u8713?\u8196?\u8899?{\sub {\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}}}{\i S}{\sub {\i i}}. From the argument made in (a), {\i x} exists in at least one equivalence class, the class which contains only {\i x} itself. This is one of ou {\i S}{\sub {\i i}} sets. Contradiction. Therefore, \u8899?{\sub {\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56491?{\sub {\i S}}}{\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Given a partition \u55349?\u56491? on a set {\i S}, show how to define a relation \u8764? on {\i S} such that {\i P} is the corresponding partition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The insight here is to build an equivalence relation such that two elements are equivalent if and only if they are part of the same subset of {\i S}, which is understood as their common equivalence class.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We define \u8764? such that \u8704?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}},\u8198?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56491?,\u8198?\u8704?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}},\u8198?\u8704?{\i y}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}},\u8198?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i y}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us prove that \u8764? is an equivalence relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 a) Reflexivity: \u8704?{\i A}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56491?,\u8198?\u8704?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i x}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 b) Symmetry: \u8704?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}},\u8198?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56491?,\u8198?\u8704?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}},\u8198?\u8704?{\i y}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}},\u8198?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i y}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i j}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i i}}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i y}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i x}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 c) Transitivity: $$\\forall S_i, S_j, S_k \\in \\mathcal\{P\}, \\forall x \\in S_i, \\forall y \\in S_j, \\forall z \\in S_k, x \\sim y \\cap y \\sim z \\\\
    \\Leftrightarrow \\\\
S_i = S_j \\cap S_j = S_k \\Rightarrow S_i = S_k \\\\
    \\Leftrightarrow \\\\
x \\sim z$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, \u8764? is indeed an equivalence relation, and is generated uniquely by the partition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 How many different equivalence relations may be defined on the set \{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\}?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If we start with the 1 element set, we have only one possible partition, one possible equivalence class.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With the 2 element set, there are 2 partitions, \{\{1,\u8198?2\}\} and \{\{1\},\u8198?\{2\}\}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With the 3 element set, there is:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 partition of type 1-1-1: \{\{1\},\u8198?\{2\},\u8198?\{3\}\}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 3 partitions of type 2-1: \{\{1\},\u8198?\{2,\u8198?3\}\}, \{\{2\},\u8198?\{1,\u8198?3\}\}, and \{\{3\},\u8198?\{1,\u8198?2\}\}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 partition of type 3: \{\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\}\}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hence, there are five equivalence classes on the 3 element set.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See the Bell numbers: https://oeis.org/A000110\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Give an example of a relation that is reflexive and symmetric, but not transitive. What happens if you attempt to use this relation to define a partition on the set?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In terms of graph theory, if we express a set with an internal relation as a graph, we can represent elements are nodes and relationships are edges. Reflexivity means that every node has a loop (unary, self-edge). Symmetry means that the graph is not directed (since every relationship goes both ways). Transitivity means that every connected subset of nodes is a maximal clique (synonymously, every connected component is a complete subgraph).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a relation which is reflexive and symmetric, but not transitive, you would have connected components of this graph which are not cliques. For these, there is ambiguity as to how you would group their nodes. Two obvious choices would be either:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab to remove the minimal number of edges to obtain n distinct cliques (thereby gaining the transitive restriction of the relation) from a given non-clique;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab to complete the connected subgraph into a clique (thereby gaining the transitive closure of the relation).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Define a relation \u8764? on the set \u8477? of real numbers, by setting {\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. Prove that this is an equivalence relation, and find a \u8217'compelling\u8217' description for \u8477?/\u8764?. Do the same for the relation \u8776? on the plane \u8477?\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8477? defined by declaring ({\i a}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i a}{\sub 2})\u8196?\u8776?\u8196?({\i b}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 2})\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i b}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484? and {\i b}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484? means that 2 real numbers differ by an integral amount. This means that the equivalence relation algebraically describes the idea that "with this relation, 2 real numbers are the same iff they have the same fractional component {\i x} (or 1\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i x} for negative numbers)". Eg, 4.76\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?1024.76\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?5.34, since \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?5.34\u8197?+\u8197?10\u8196?=\u8196?4.76, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To make an algebraic quotient of a set by an equivalence relation, we take the function which maps each element to its corresponding equivalence class, in the set (partition) containing these equivalence class. Intuitively, this is similar to keeping only one representative element per equivalence class. For the example class above, we can keep the representative 0.76. There is such an equivalence class for every fractional part possible, that is, one for every number in [0,\u8198?1[. The corresponding map is the "real remainder of division modulo 1". This map is well-defined because each real number has only one output for this map, and all real numbers that are equivalent through \u8764? are mapped to the same value in the output set.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We should also notice that since 0\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?1, this space loops around on itself. Intuitively, if you increase linearly in the input space \u8477?, it goes back to 0 after 0.9999999... in the output space. This output space is thus a circle of perimeter 1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, {\i b}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484? and {\i b}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484? means that 2 points in the 2D plane are the same iff they differ in each coordinate by an integral amount. This boils down to combining two such loops from the first part of the exercise: one in the {\i x} direction and one in the {\i y} direction: what this gives is the small square [0,\u8198?1[\u8197?\u215?\u8197?[0,\u8198?1[, which loops to {\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?0 (resp. {\i y}\u8196?=\u8196?0) when {\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?1 (resp. {\i y}\u8196?=\u8196?1) is reached. This space functions like a small torus, of area 1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Section 2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 How many different bijections are there between a set {\i S} with {\i n} elements and itself?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any bijection is a choice of a pairs from 2 sets of the same size, where each element is used only once, and each pair has one element from each set. At first there are n choices in each set. If we pick a pair, we pick from {\i n}{\super 2} possibilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are then ({\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1){\super 2} choices of pairs left, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ccl\u176?: $\\prod_\{i=1\}^\{i=n\} i^2 = (n!)^2$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that a function has a right-inverse iff it is surjective (can use AC)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.2.a) \u8658?: Suppose that {\i f} has a right-inverse (pre-inverse).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We have \u8707?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i B}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i f} is not a a surjection. This means \u8707?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?\u8708?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i a})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f}({\i g}({\i b}))\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i B}}({\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b} Necessarily, {\i g}({\i b}) is such an {\i a}, so \u8707?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i a}). Contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ccl\u176?:: f is a surjection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.2.b) \u8656?: Suppose that f is a surjection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?\u8707?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i a})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will construct a pre-inverse for {\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The insight here is to realize that a surjection divides its input set into a partition, where each 2-by-2 disjoint subset corresponds to {\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i q}\}), for every {\i q} in the output set. More formally, each "fiber" (preimage of a singleton) is a disjoint subset of the input set, and the union of fibers is the input set itself. You can see this in the following diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (add diagram) 1234 to ab 1a 2a (fiber from a) 3b 4b (fiber from b) https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/157450/producing-a-diagram-showing-relations-between-sets https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/79009/drawing-the-mapping-of-elements-for-sets-in-latex\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using AC, we select a single element from each such fiber. For each {\i q}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B}, we name {\i p}{\sub {\i q}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i q}\}) the chosen element. We define {\i g} as {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i q}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i p}{\sub {\i q}}). With this, \u8704?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}({\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b}, and so {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}. Thus, {\i f} has a preinverse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A summary of this idea: all surjection preinverses are simply a choice of a representative for each fiber of the surjection as the output to the respective singleton.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that the inverse of a bijection is a bijection, and that the composition of two bijections is a bijection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.3.a) Using the fact that a function is a bijection iff it has a two-sided \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 inverse (\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Corollary 2.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 we can see from this defining fact, {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B})bijective \u8660?,\u8707?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i B}} that {\i f} is naturally {\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8217's (unique) two-sided inverse, and so {\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} is also a bijection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.3.b) Let be {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}),\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i C}), both bijective (hence with \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 inverses in the respective function spaces). Let {\i h}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i C}),\u8198?{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} and {\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}. We have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
h^\{-1\} \\circ h &= (f^\{-1\} \\circ g^\{-1\}) \\circ (g \\circ f) \\\\
               &=  f^\{-1\} \\circ g^\{-1\}  \\circ  g \\circ f  \\\\
               &=  f^\{-1\} \\circ          id_B    \\circ f  \\\\
               &=  f^\{-1\} \\circ                        f  \\\\
               &=  id_A
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
h \\circ h^\{-1\} &= (g \\circ f) \\circ (f^\{-1\} \\circ g^\{-1\}) \\\\
               &=  g \\circ f  \\circ  f^\{-1\} \\circ g^\{-1\}  \\\\
               &=  g \\circ     id_B         \\circ g^\{-1\}  \\\\
               &=  g \\circ                        g^\{-1\}  \\\\
               &=  id_C
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore {\i h} and {\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} are two-sided inverses of each other, and thus bijections. From this we conclude that the composition of any two bijections is also a bijection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that \u8216'isomorphism\u8217' is an equivalence relation (on any set of sets).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.4.a) Problem statement\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let \u55349?\u56476? be a set of sets. We define the relation \u8771? between the elements of \u55349?\u56476? as the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i X},\u8198?{\i Y}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56476?,\u8197?{\i X}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i Y}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?there exists a bijection between {\i X} and {\i Y}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us show that \u8771? is an equivalence relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.4.b) Reflexivity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For any set {\i A}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56476?, the identity mapping on {\i A} is a bijection. This means that \u8704?{\i A}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u55349?\u56476?,\u8198?{\i A}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}, ie, \u8771? is reflexive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 2.4.c) Symmetry\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
\\forall X, Y \\in \\mathcal\{A\}, \\; X \\simeq Y & \\Rightarrow \\exists f      \\in (X \\to Y) \\text\{ bijective\} \\\\
                                            & \\Rightarrow \\exists f^\{-1\} \\in (Y \\to X) \\text\{ bijective\} \\\\
                                            & \\Rightarrow Y \\simeq X
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, \u8771? is symmetric.\par}
