{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There exists no map {\i \u963?} such that the following diagram commutes (since the output of {\i f}{\sub 1} will always be null in its second coordinate, and the output of {\i f}{\sub 2} will always be null in the first):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now, let us prove that \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} is indeed a category for an arbitrary object {\i A} of an arbitrary category \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.1.a) Identity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A generic identity morphism is expressed diagrammatically in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that since {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i Z}} in \u55349?\u56478?, this is compatible with the definition of a (pre-/right-)unit morphism in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}}. Also, since the only maps post-{\i f} are maps from {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}, we have {\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}} as the (post-/left-)unit for every morphism {\i f} (ie, {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.1.b) Composition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Taking 3 objects of the slice category ({\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}), {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) and {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A})), and two morphisms ({\i \u963?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 2} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u963?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}), and {\i \u964?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 2} to {\i f}{\sub 3} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u964?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 3})), we have that {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u963?} and {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub 3}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u964?}. This is expressed as the following commutative diagram.\par}
